{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1677"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1677"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.28,0.05,0.19,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101356"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1677"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83786"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"889"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5341"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42366"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101356"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old farmer presents to his General Practitioner (GP) with a growth on his right ear. He explains that it only appeared around four months ago as a small bump and has grown rapidly. The GP does a complete skin examination and does not find any similar lesions. His skin is obviously sun-damaged. The lesion is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal cell carcinoma","Pyogenic granuloma","Kaposi sarcoma","Keratoacanthoma","Fibroxanthoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroxanthomas (atypical fibroxanthoma)\u003C/strong\u003E are a low-grade malignant rapidly growing nodular dermal neoplasm that tend to appear in sun-damaged areas of skin in older patients. It is often ulcerated, and may be pink or red but usually less than 2 cm in diameter. There are many histologic variants and may also involve osteoclast giant cells. The diagnosis is based on those three factors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Erapidity of growth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esun-damaged skin (either ultraviolet light from sun or solarium or radiotherapy)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eolder patient over 70 or 80 years of age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst it is not a common skin cancer, it is an important differential to be aware of and a good learning point. Squamous cell carcinoma, melanoma, merkel cell carcinoma and some basal cell carcinomas can also have rapid growth and may be only be differentiated by tissue diagnosis. Malignant fibrous histiocytomas (MFH) are also histologically similar to fibroxanthomas, and so may be regarded as a superficial variant of MFH (ie. not involving the subcutis or deeper).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst some basal cell carcinomas may grow quickly, typically a basal cell carcinoma presents as a slowly growing lesion over months. They also may ulcerate and present in the elderly population. However they typically present as pearly pink nodules with telangiectasia, or flat scaley non-healing lesions which is different in appearance for this scenario. Whilst it should be a differential diagnosis, the most likely diagnosis in this scenario is fibroxanthomas for the appearance and rapid growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratoacanthomas\u003C/strong\u003E are also rapidly growing, they typically have a dome-like appearance and central plug of necrotic tissue which is not present in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EKaposi sarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E, often associated with HIV infection, present in various forms. They can appear as red to purple macules, papules and nodules, and may present anywhere on the body, including mucous membranes of the mouth, nose and throat, rather than a single ulcerating lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyogenic granulomas\u003C/strong\u003E are often 5-10mm in size and present as a painless red nodule that commonly grows on the fingers or face. The lesion may be smooth as it grows but it can ulcerate and become crusty.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fibroxanthomas grow rapidly and most often present in older individuals on sun-exposed skin."],"references":["Helbig, D., Ziemer, M., Dippel, E., Erdmann, M., Hillen, U., Leiter, U., Mentzel, T., Osterhoff, G., Ugurel, S., Utikal, J., von Bubnoff, D., Weishaupt, C. and Grabbe, S. (2022), S1-guideline atypical fibroxanthoma (AFX) and pleomorphic dermal sarcoma (PDS). JDDG: Journal der Deutschen Dermatologischen Gesellschaft, 20: 235-243. https://doi.org/10.1111/ddg.14700","Sakamoto, A. Atypical Fibroxanthoma. Clinical Medical Oncology. 2008: 2 (117 - 127). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles","Gill P, Aung P. Skin nonmelanocytic: Fibrous, fibrohistiocytic and myofibroblastic neoplasms: atypical fibroxanthoma.  Pathology Outlines. 2021. Available at: https://www.pathologyoutlines.com/topic/skintumornonmelanocyticAFX.html","How to cite this article: Perandones Gonz\u00e1lez H, Valladares Narganes LM, Gonz\u00e1lez Mor\u00e1n MA, Rodr\u00edguez prieto M\u00c1. Collision of basal cell carcinoma and atypical fibroxanthoma. Indian J Dermatol Venereol Leprol. 2024;90:500-3. Available at: https://ijdvl.com/collision-of-basal-cell-carcinoma-and-atypical-fibroxanthoma/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83786"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1677"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15739"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15739"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/edd5590a-d628-4c1d-975d-16cbefd7686c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/edd5590a-d628-4c1d-975d-16cbefd7686c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83786"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T14:26:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-31T11:50:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1677"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101356"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic